SIMPLE: preponderancy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preponderancy
<hw>Pre*pon"der*an*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧pond⟦eacute⟧rance</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
quality or state of being preponderant; superiority or excess of weight,
influence, or power, etc.; an outweighing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mind should . . . reject or receive proportionably to the
<qex>preponderancy</qex> of the greater grounds of probability.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a few weeks he had changed the relative position of all the
states in Europe, and had restored the equilibrium which the
<qex>preponderance</qex> of one power had destroyed.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>The excess of weight of that part
of a canon behind the trunnions over that in front of them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preponderant</ent>⟦br⟧
